# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alan-mchughen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] McHughen served as an Assistant then full Professor and Research Scientist with the University of Saskatchewan from 1982 to 2002.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] He currently leads the McHughen Research Group at the University of California, Riverside, in the Department of Botany and Plant Sciences.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] From 2011 to 2012 McHughen served as a Jefferson Science Fellow and Senior Policy Analyst in the Executive Office of the President in the Obama administration.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] McHughen is a past-President of the International Society for Biosafety Research, a fellow with the American College of Nutrition (2002), a AAAS Fellow with the American Association for the Advancement of Science (2010), and member of the American Society of Plant Biology.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] McHughen received the Robert Anderson Fellowship in Biochemistry from Yale University and a research fellowship from the Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] He also received the Science in Society Book of the Year Award in 2000 from the Science Writers & Communicators of Canada, the Certificate of Merit from the U.S.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] Department of Agriculture in 2006, and the Distinguished Lecturer Award from the U.S.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] Environmental Protection Agency in 2001.
[src:alan-mchughen/alan-mchughen] McHughen is the author of numerous peer-reviewed research articles, academic papers, and contributor to text books on the issue of genetically modified crops.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The **American Nutrition Association** (**ANA**) is a 501(c)(3) charitable non-profit organization established to encourage the scientific investigation of nutrition and metabolism.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The ANA publishes the ***Journal of the American Nutrition Association*** and hosts scientific conferences in the U.S. and in Europe.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] It is headquartered in Hinsdale, Illinois.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] Previously known as the American College of Nutrition, in 2019 together with the Board for Certification of Nutrition Specialists, the Center for Nutrition Advocacy, and the American Nutrition Association Foundation, affiliated together as the American Nutrition Association.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The four organizations remain legally independent entities but share a single website together.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] In October 2010, the American College of Nutrition and American Society for Nutrition proposed to merge.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The ANA is governed by a member-elected Board of Directors and the current CEO of ANA is Michael Stroka.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The organization also has several advisory components which include a Scientific Advisory Board, Strategic Advisory Board, Ketogenic Nutrition Training Program Development Team, and a Nutritional Genomics Advisory Panel.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The European chapter of the American Nutrition Association was established in 2001.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] In 2011 the ANA said that its European chapter had hosted eight scientific conferences.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] Members of the American Nutrition Association are clinicians, researchers and academicians, medical students, and international nutritionists.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] Categories of membership include Professional Member, Student Member, Professional Associate, and Nutrition Enthusiast.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The *Journal of the American Nutrition Association* (*JANA*) is a peer-reviewed journal published eight times a year by ANA.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] It has an impact factor of 3.571 as of 2021.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The *JANA* is abstracted or indexed in Current Contents, Index Medicus, MEDLINE, Science Citation Index, SciSearch, Research Alert, Chemical Abstracts, CAB International and BIOSIS.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] According to the *Integrity in Science* project, the *Journal of the American College of Nutrition*, now the *Journal of the American Nutrition Association*, failed to disclose the ties of the editor and authors of their June 2006 supplement on sodium to the food industry.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The Editor in Chief subsequently published a letter in the journal noting the ambiguity in the conflict of interest disclosure process then in place and a new documentation procedure was put in place to remedy this.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] Through 2021 the organization had held 62 annual scientific conferences.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] The organization accepted funding from for-profit corporations until 2011.
[src:alan-mchughen/american-college-of-nutrition] "The American College of Nutrition accepts no funding from for-profit corporations.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, new techniques were developed for the study of plants, including methods of optical microscopy and live cell imaging, electron microscopy, analysis of chromosome number, plant chemistry and the structure and function of enzymes and other proteins.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In the last two decades of the 20th century, botanists exploited the techniques of molecular genetic analysis, including genomics and proteomics and DNA sequences to classify plants more accurately.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Modern botany is a broad subject with contributions and insights from most other areas of science and technology.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Research topics include the study of plant structure, growth and differentiation, reproduction, biochemistry and primary metabolism, chemical products, development, diseases, evolutionary relationships, systematics, and plant taxonomy.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Dominant themes in 21st-century plant science are molecular genetics and epigenetics, which study the mechanisms and control of gene expression during differentiation of plant cells and tissues.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The term "botany" comes from the Ancient Greek word **botanē** (βοτάνη) meaning "pasture", "herbs" "grass", or "fodder"; **Botanē** is in turn derived from **boskein** (Greek: βόσκειν), "to feed" or "to graze".
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Traditionally, botany has also included the study of fungi and algae by mycologists and phycologists respectively, with the study of these three groups of organisms remaining within the sphere of interest of the International Botanical Congress.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botany originated as herbalism, the study and use of plants for their possible medicinal properties.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The early recorded history of botany includes many ancient writings and plant classifications.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Examples of early botanical works have been found in ancient texts from India dating back to before 1100 BCE, Ancient Egypt, in archaic Avestan writings, and in works from China purportedly from before 221 BCE.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Modern botany traces its roots back to Ancient Greece specifically to Theophrastus (c.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] 371–287 BCE), a student of Aristotle who invented and described many of its principles and is widely regarded in the scientific community as the "Father of Botany".
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] His major works, *Enquiry into Plants* and *On the Causes of Plants*, constitute the most important contributions to botanical science until the Middle Ages, almost seventeen centuries later.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Another work from Ancient Greece that made an early impact on botany is *De materia medica*, a five-volume encyclopaedia about preliminary herbal medicine written in the middle of the first century by Greek physician and pharmacologist Pedanius Dioscorides.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] *De materia medica* was widely read for more than 1,500 years.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Important contributions from the medieval Muslim world include Ibn Wahshiyya's *Nabatean Agriculture*, Abū Ḥanīfa Dīnawarī's (828–896) the *Book of Plants*, and Ibn Bassal's *The Classification of Soils*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In the early 13th century, Abu al-Abbas al-Nabati, and Ibn al-Baitar (d.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] 1248) wrote on botany in a systematic and scientific manner.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In the mid-16th century, botanical gardens were founded in a number of Italian universities.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The Padua botanical garden in 1545 is usually considered to be the first that is still in its original location.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These gardens continued the practical value of earlier "physic gardens", often associated with monasteries, in which plants were cultivated for suspected medicinal uses.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] They supported the growth of botany as an academic subject.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Lectures were given about the plants grown in the gardens.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botanical gardens came much later to northern Europe; the first in England was the University of Oxford Botanic Garden in 1621.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] German physician Leonhart Fuchs (1501–1566) was one of "the three German fathers of botany", along with theologian Otto Brunfels (1489–1534) and physician Hieronymus Bock (1498–1554) (also called Hieronymus Tragus).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Fuchs and Brunfels broke away from the tradition of copying earlier works to make original observations of their own.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Bock created his own system of plant classification.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Physician Valerius Cordus (1515–1544) authored a botanically and pharmacologically important herbal *Historia Plantarum* in 1544 and a pharmacopoeia of lasting importance, the *Dispensatorium* in 1546.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Naturalist Conrad von Gesner (1516–1565) and herbalist John Gerard (1545 – c.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] 1611) published herbals covering the supposed medicinal uses of plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Naturalist Ulisse Aldrovandi (1522–1605) was considered the *father of natural history*, which included the study of plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In 1665, using an early microscope, Polymath Robert Hooke discovered cells (a term he coined) in cork, and a short time later in living plant tissue.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] During the 18th century, systems of plant identification were developed comparable to dichotomous keys, where unidentified plants are placed into taxonomic groups (e.g. family, genus and species) by making a series of choices between pairs of characters.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The choice and sequence of the characters may be artificial in keys designed purely for identification (diagnostic keys) or more closely related to the natural or phyletic order of the taxa in synoptic keys.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] By the 18th century, new plants for study were arriving in Europe in increasing numbers from newly discovered countries and the European colonies worldwide.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In 1753, Carl Linnaeus published his Species Plantarum, a hierarchical classification of plant species that remains the reference point for modern botanical nomenclature.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This established a standardised binomial or two-part naming scheme where the first name represented the genus and the second identified the species within the genus.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] For the purposes of identification, Linnaeus's *Systema Sexuale* classified plants into 24 groups according to the number of their male sexual organs.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The 24th group, *Cryptogamia*, included all plants with concealed reproductive parts: mosses, liverworts, ferns, algae and fungi.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Increasing knowledge of plant anatomy, morphology and life cycles led to the realisation that there were more natural affinities between plants than the artificial sexual system of Linnaeus.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Adanson (1763), de Jussieu (1789), and Candolle (1819) all proposed various alternative natural systems of classification that grouped plants using a wider range of shared characters and were widely followed.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The Candollean system reflected his ideas of the progression of morphological complexity and the later Bentham & Hooker system, which was influential until the mid-19th century, was influenced by Candolle's approach.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Darwin's publication of the *Origin of Species* in 1859 and his concept of common descent required modifications to the Candollean system to reflect evolutionary relationships as distinct from mere morphological similarity.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In the 19th century botany was a socially acceptable hobby for upper-class women.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These women would collect and paint flowers and plants from around the world with scientific accuracy.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The paintings were used to record many species that could not be transported or maintained in other environments.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Marianne North illustrated over 900 species in extreme detail with watercolour and oil paintings.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Her work and many other women's botany work was the beginning of popularising botany to a wider audience.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botany was greatly stimulated by the appearance of the first "modern" textbook, Matthias Schleiden's **Grundzüge der Wissenschaftlichen Botanik**, published in English in 1849 as *Principles of Scientific Botany*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Schleiden was a microscopist and an early plant anatomist who co-founded the cell theory with Theodor Schwann and Rudolf Virchow and was among the first to grasp the significance of the cell nucleus that had been described by Robert Brown in 1831.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In 1855, Adolf Fick formulated Fick's laws that enabled the calculation of the rates of molecular diffusion in biological systems.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Building upon the gene-chromosome theory of heredity that originated with Gregor Mendel (1822–1884), August Weismann (1834–1914) proved that inheritance only takes place through gametes.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] No other cells can pass on inherited characters.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The work of Katherine Esau (1898–1997) on plant anatomy is still a major foundation of modern botany.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Her books *Plant Anatomy* and *Anatomy of Seed Plants* have been key plant structural biology texts for more than half a century.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The discipline of plant ecology was pioneered in the late 19th century by botanists such as Eugenius Warming, who produced the hypothesis that plants form communities, and his mentor and successor Christen C.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Raunkiær whose system for describing plant life forms is still in use today.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The concept that the composition of plant communities such as temperate broadleaf forest changes by a process of ecological succession was developed by Henry Chandler Cowles, Arthur Tansley and Frederic Clements.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Clements is credited with the idea of climax vegetation as the most complex vegetation that an environment can support and Tansley introduced the concept of ecosystems to biology.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Building on the extensive earlier work of Alphonse de Candolle, Nikolai Vavilov (1887–1943) produced accounts of the biogeography, centres of origin, and evolutionary history of economic plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These developments, coupled with new methods for measuring the size of stomatal apertures, and the rate of photosynthesis have enabled a precise description of the rates of gas exchange between plants and the atmosphere.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Innovations in statistical analysis by Ronald Fisher, Frank Yates and others at Rothamsted Experimental Station facilitated rational experimental design and data analysis in botanical research.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The discovery and identification of the auxin plant hormones by Kenneth V.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Thimann in 1948 enabled the regulation of plant growth by externally applied chemicals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Frederick Campion Steward pioneered techniques of micropropagation and plant tissue culture controlled by plant hormones.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The synthetic auxin 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid or 2,4-D was one of the first commercial synthetic herbicides.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] 20th century developments in plant biochemistry have been driven by modern techniques of organic chemical analysis, such as spectroscopy, chromatography and electrophoresis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These technologies enable the biotechnological use of whole plants or plant cell cultures grown in bioreactors to synthesise pesticides, antibiotics or other pharmaceuticals, as well as the practical application of genetically modified crops designed for traits such as improved yield.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Modern morphology recognises a continuum between the major morphological categories of root, stem (caulome), leaf (phyllome) and trichome.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Furthermore, it emphasises structural dynamics.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Modern systematics aims to reflect and discover phylogenetic relationships between plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Modern molecular phylogenetics largely ignores morphological characters, relying on DNA sequences as data.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Molecular analysis of DNA sequences from most families of flowering plants enabled the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group to publish in 1998 a phylogeny of flowering plants, answering many of the questions about relationships among angiosperm families and species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The theoretical possibility of a practical method for the identification of plant species and commercial varieties by DNA barcoding is the subject of active current research.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some subfields of botany relate to particular groups of organisms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Divisions related to the broader historical sense of botany include *bacteriology*, *mycology* (or *fungology*), and *phycology* – respectively, the study of bacteria, fungi, and algae – with *lichenology* as a subfield of mycology.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The narrower sense of botany as the study of embryophytes (land plants) is called *phytology*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] *Bryology* is the study of mosses (and in the broader sense also liverworts and hornworts).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] *Pteridology* (or *filicology*) is the study of ferns and allied plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] A number of other taxa of ranks varying from family to subgenus have terms for their study, including *agrostology* (or *graminology*) for the study of grasses, *synantherology* for the study of composites, and *batology* for the study of brambles.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Study can also be divided by guild rather than clade or grade.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] For example, *dendrology* is the study of woody plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Many divisions of biology have botanical subfields.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These are commonly denoted by prefixing the word plant (e.g. plant taxonomy, plant ecology, plant anatomy, plant morphology, plant systematics), or prefixing or substituting the prefix phyto- (e.g. phytochemistry, phytogeography).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The study of fossil plants is called *palaeobotany*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Other fields are denoted by adding or substituting the word botany (e.g. systematic botany).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The intersection of fields from the above pair of categories gives rise to fields such as *bryogeography*, the study of the distribution of mosses.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Different parts of plants also give rise to their own subfields, including *xylology*, *carpology* (or *fructology*), and *palynology*, these being the study of wood, fruit and pollen/spores respectively.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botany also overlaps on the one hand with agriculture, horticulture and silviculture, and on the other hand with medicine and pharmacology, giving rise to fields such as *agronomy*, *horticultural botany*, *phytopathology*, and *phytopharmacology*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The study of plants is vital because they underpin almost all animal life on Earth by generating a large proportion of the oxygen and food that provide humans and other organisms with aerobic respiration with the chemical energy they need to exist.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] As a by-product of photosynthesis, plants release oxygen into the atmosphere, a gas that is required by nearly all living things to carry out cellular respiration.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In addition, they are influential in the global carbon and water cycles and plant roots bind and stabilise soils, preventing soil erosion.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plants are crucial to the future of human society as they provide food, oxygen, biochemicals, and products for people, as well as creating and preserving soil.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Historically, all living things were classified as either animals or plants and botany covered the study of all organisms not considered animals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botanists examine both the internal functions and processes within plant organelles, cells, tissues, whole plants, plant populations and plant communities.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] At each of these levels, a botanist may be concerned with the classification (taxonomy), phylogeny and evolution, structure (anatomy and morphology), or function (physiology) of plant life.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The strictest definition of "plant" includes only the "land plants" or embryophytes, which include seed plants (gymnosperms, including the pines, and flowering plants) and the free-sporing cryptogams including ferns, clubmosses, liverworts, hornworts and mosses.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Embryophytes are multicellular eukaryotes descended from an ancestor that obtained its energy from sunlight by photosynthesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] They have life cycles with alternating haploid and diploid phases.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The sexual haploid phase of embryophytes, known as the gametophyte, nurtures the developing diploid embryo sporophyte within its tissues for at least part of its life, even in the seed plants, where the gametophyte itself is nurtured by its parent sporophyte.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Other groups of organisms that were previously studied by botanists include bacteria (now studied in bacteriology), fungi (mycology) – including lichen-forming fungi (lichenology), non-chlorophyte algae (phycology), and viruses (virology).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] However, attention is still given to these groups by botanists, and fungi (including lichens) and photosynthetic protists are usually covered in introductory botany courses.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Palaeobotanists study ancient plants in the fossil record to provide information about the evolutionary history of plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Cyanobacteria, the first oxygen-releasing photosynthetic organisms on Earth, are thought to have given rise to the ancestor of plants by entering into an endosymbiotic relationship with an early eukaryote, ultimately becoming the chloroplasts in plant cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The new photosynthetic plants (along with their algal relatives) accelerated the rise in atmospheric oxygen started by the cyanobacteria, changing the ancient oxygen-free, reducing, atmosphere to one in which free oxygen has been abundant for more than 2 billion years.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Virtually all staple foods come either directly from primary production by plants, or indirectly from animals that eat them.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plants and other photosynthetic organisms are at the base of most food chains because they use the energy from the sun and nutrients from the soil and atmosphere, converting them into a form that can be used by animals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This is what ecologists call the first trophic level.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botanists study how plants produce food and how to increase yields, for example through plant breeding, making their work important to humanity's ability to feed the world and provide food security for future generations.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Botanists also study weeds, which are a considerable problem in agriculture, and the biology and control of plant pathogens in agriculture and natural ecosystems.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Ethnobotany is the study of the relationships between plants and people.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] When applied to the investigation of historical plant–people relationships ethnobotany may be referred to as archaeobotany or palaeoethnobotany.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plant biochemistry is the study of the chemical processes used by plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some of these processes are used in their primary metabolism like the photosynthetic Calvin cycle and crassulacean acid metabolism.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Others make specialised materials like the cellulose and lignin used to build their bodies, and secondary products like resins and aroma compounds.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plants and various other groups of photosynthetic eukaryotes collectively known as "algae" have unique organelles known as chloroplasts.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Chloroplasts are thought to be descended from cyanobacteria that formed endosymbiotic relationships with ancient plant and algal ancestors.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Chloroplasts and cyanobacteria contain the blue-green pigment chlorophyll *a*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Chlorophyll *a* (as well as its plant and green algal-specific cousin chlorophyll *b*) absorbs light in the blue-violet and orange/red parts of the spectrum while reflecting and transmitting the green light that we see as the characteristic colour of these organisms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The energy in the red and blue light that these pigments absorb is used by chloroplasts to make energy-rich carbon compounds from carbon dioxide and water by oxygenic photosynthesis, a process that generates molecular oxygen (O2) as a by-product.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The light energy captured by chlorophyll *a* is initially in the form of electrons (and later a proton gradient) that is used to make molecules of ATP and NADPH which temporarily store and transport energy.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Their energy is used in the light-independent reactions of the Calvin cycle by the enzyme rubisco to produce molecules of the 3-carbon sugar glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is the first product of photosynthesis and the raw material from which glucose and almost all other organic molecules of biological origin are synthesised.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some of the glucose is converted to starch which is stored in the chloroplast.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Starch is the characteristic energy store of most land plants and algae, while inulin, a polymer of fructose is used for the same purpose in the sunflower family Asteraceae.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some of the glucose is converted to sucrose (common table sugar) for export to the rest of the plant.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Unlike in animals (which lack chloroplasts), plants and their eukaryote relatives have delegated many biochemical roles to their chloroplasts, including synthesising all their fatty acids, and most amino acids.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The fatty acids that chloroplasts make are used for many things, such as providing material to build cell membranes out of and making the polymer cutin which is found in the plant cuticle that protects land plants from drying out.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plants synthesise a number of unique polymers like the polysaccharide molecules cellulose, pectin and xyloglucan from which the land plant cell wall is constructed.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Vascular land plants make lignin, a polymer used to strengthen the secondary cell walls of xylem tracheids and vessels to keep them from collapsing when a plant sucks water through them under water stress.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Lignin is also used in other cell types like sclerenchyma fibres that provide structural support for a plant and is a major constituent of wood.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Sporopollenin is a chemically resistant polymer found in the outer cell walls of spores and pollen of land plants responsible for the survival of early land plant spores and the pollen of seed plants in the fossil record.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] It is widely regarded as a marker for the start of land plant evolution during the Ordovician period.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere today is much lower than it was when plants emerged onto land during the Ordovician and Silurian periods.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These biochemical strategies are unique to land plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Phytochemistry is a branch of plant biochemistry primarily concerned with the chemical substances produced by plants during secondary metabolism.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some of these compounds are toxins such as the alkaloid coniine from hemlock.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Others, such as the essential oils peppermint oil and lemon oil are useful for their aroma, as flavourings and spices (e.g., capsaicin), and in medicine as pharmaceuticals as in opium from opium poppies.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Many medicinal and recreational drugs, such as tetrahydrocannabinol (active ingredient in cannabis), caffeine, morphine and nicotine come directly from plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Others are simple derivatives of botanical natural products.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] For example, the pain killer aspirin is the acetyl ester of salicylic acid, originally isolated from the bark of willow trees, and a wide range of opiate painkillers like heroin are obtained by chemical modification of morphine obtained from the opium poppy.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Popular stimulants come from plants, such as caffeine from coffee, tea and chocolate, and nicotine from tobacco.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Most alcoholic beverages come from fermentation of carbohydrate-rich plant products such as barley (beer), rice (sake) and grapes (wine).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Native Americans have used various plants as ways of treating illness or disease for thousands of years.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This knowledge Native Americans have on plants has been recorded by enthnobotanists and then in turn has been used by pharmaceutical companies as a way of drug discovery.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Sugar, starch, cotton, linen, hemp, some types of rope, wood and particle boards, papyrus and paper, vegetable oils, wax, and natural rubber are examples of commercially important materials made from plant tissues or their secondary products.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Charcoal, a pure form of carbon made by pyrolysis of wood, has a long history as a metal-smelting fuel, as a filter material and adsorbent and as an artist's material and is one of the three ingredients of gunpowder.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Cellulose, the world's most abundant organic polymer, can be converted into energy, fuels, materials and chemical feedstock.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Products made from cellulose include rayon and cellophane, wallpaper paste, biobutanol and gun cotton.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Sugarcane, rapeseed and soy are some of the plants with a highly fermentable sugar or oil content that are used as sources of biofuels, important alternatives to fossil fuels, such as biodiesel.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Sweetgrass was used by Native Americans to ward off bugs like mosquitoes.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These bug repelling properties of sweetgrass were later found by the American Chemical Society in the molecules phytol and coumarin.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plant ecology is the science of the functional relationships between plants and their habitats – the environments where they complete their life cycles.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plant ecologists study the composition of local and regional floras, their biodiversity, genetic diversity and fitness, the adaptation of plants to their environment, and their competitive or mutualistic interactions with other species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some ecologists even rely on empirical data from indigenous people that is gathered by ethnobotanists.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This information can relay a great deal of information on how the land once was, thousands of years ago, and how it has changed over that time.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The goals of plant ecology are to understand the causes of their distribution patterns, productivity, environmental impact, evolution, and responses to environmental change.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plants depend on certain edaphic (soil) and climatic factors in their environment but can modify these factors too.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] For example, they can change their environment's albedo, increase runoff interception, stabilise mineral soils and develop their organic content, and affect local temperature.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plants compete with other organisms in their ecosystem for resources.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] They interact with their neighbours at a variety of spatial scales in groups, populations and communities that collectively constitute vegetation.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Regions with characteristic vegetation types and dominant plants as well as similar abiotic and biotic factors, climate, and geography make up biomes like tundra or tropical rainforest.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Herbivores eat plants, but plants can defend themselves, and some species are parasitic or even carnivorous.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Other organisms form mutually beneficial relationships with plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] For example, mycorrhizal fungi and rhizobia provide plants with nutrients in exchange for food; ants are recruited by ant plants to provide protection; honey bees, bats and other animals pollinate flowers; and humans and other animals act as dispersal vectors to spread spores and seeds.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Plant responses to climate and other environmental changes can inform one's understanding of how these changes affect ecosystem function and productivity.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] For example, plant phenology can be a useful proxy for temperature in historical climatology, and the biological impact of climate change and global warming.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Palynology, the analysis of fossil pollen deposits in sediments from thousands or millions of years ago allows the reconstruction of past climates.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Estimates of atmospheric CO2 concentrations since the Palaeozoic have been obtained from stomatal densities and the leaf shapes and sizes of ancient land plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Ozone depletion can expose plants to higher levels of ultraviolet radiation-B (UV-B), resulting in lower growth rates.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Moreover, information from studies of community ecology, plant systematics, and taxonomy is essential to understanding vegetation change, habitat destruction and species extinction.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Inheritance in plants follows the same fundamental principles of genetics as in other multicellular organisms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Gregor Mendel discovered the genetic laws of inheritance by studying inherited traits such as shape in *Pisum sativum* (peas).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] What Mendel learned from studying plants has had far-reaching benefits outside of botany.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Similarly, "jumping genes" were discovered by Barbara McClintock while she was studying maize.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Nevertheless, there are some distinctive genetic differences between plants and other organisms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Species boundaries in plants may be weaker than in animals, and cross species hybrids are often possible.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] A familiar example is peppermint, *Mentha* × *piperita*, a sterile hybrid between *Mentha aquatica* and spearmint, *Mentha spicata*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The many cultivated varieties of wheat are the result of multiple inter- and intra-specific crosses between wild species and their hybrids.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Angiosperms with monoecious flowers often have self-incompatibility mechanisms that operate between the pollen and stigma so that the pollen either fails to reach the stigma or fails to germinate and produce male gametes.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This is one of several methods used by plants to promote outcrossing.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] In many land plants the male and female gametes are produced by separate individuals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These species are said to be dioecious when referring to vascular plant sporophytes and dioicous when referring to bryophyte gametophytes.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This beneficial effect is also known as hybrid vigour or heterosis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Once outcrossing is established, subsequent switching to inbreeding becomes disadvantageous since it allows expression of the previously masked deleterious recessive mutations, commonly referred to as inbreeding depression.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Unlike in higher animals, where parthenogenesis is rare, asexual reproduction may occur in plants by several different mechanisms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The formation of stem tubers in potato is one example.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Particularly in arctic or alpine habitats, where opportunities for fertilisation of flowers by animals are rare, plantlets or bulbs may develop instead of flowers, replacing sexual reproduction with asexual reproduction and giving rise to clonal populations genetically identical to the parent.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This is one of several types of apomixis that occur in plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Apomixis can also happen in a seed, producing a seed that contains an embryo genetically identical to the parent.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Most sexually reproducing organisms are diploid, with paired chromosomes, but doubling of their chromosome number may occur due to errors in cytokinesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] This can occur early in development to produce an autopolyploid or partly autopolyploid organism, or during normal processes of cellular differentiation to produce some cell types that are polyploid (endopolyploidy), or during gamete formation.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] An allopolyploid plant may result from a hybridisation event between two different species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Both autopolyploid and allopolyploid plants can often reproduce normally, but may be unable to cross-breed successfully with the parent population because there is a mismatch in chromosome numbers.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These plants that are reproductively isolated from the parent species but live within the same geographical area, may be sufficiently successful to form a new species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some otherwise sterile plant polyploids can still reproduce vegetatively or by seed apomixis, forming clonal populations of identical individuals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Durum wheat is a fertile tetraploid allopolyploid, while bread wheat is a fertile hexaploid.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The commercial banana is an example of a sterile, seedless triploid hybrid.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Common dandelion is a triploid that produces viable seeds by apomictic seed.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] As in other eukaryotes, the inheritance of endosymbiotic organelles like mitochondria and chloroplasts in plants is non-Mendelian.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Chloroplasts are inherited through the male parent in gymnosperms but often through the female parent in flowering plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] A considerable amount of new knowledge about plant function comes from studies of the molecular genetics of model plants such as the Thale cress, *Arabidopsis thaliana*, a weedy species in the mustard family (Brassicaceae).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The genome or hereditary information contained in the genes of this species is encoded by about 135 million base pairs of DNA, forming one of the smallest genomes among flowering plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] *Arabidopsis* was the first plant to have its genome sequenced, in 2000.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The sequencing of some other relatively small genomes, of rice (*Oryza sativa*) and *Brachypodium distachyon*, has made them important model species for understanding the genetics, cellular and molecular biology of cereals, grasses and monocots generally.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Model plants such as *Arabidopsis thaliana* are used for studying the molecular biology of plant cells and the chloroplast.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Ideally, these organisms have small genomes that are well known or completely sequenced, small stature and short generation times.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Corn has been used to study mechanisms of photosynthesis and phloem loading of sugar in C4 plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The single-celled green alga *Chlamydomonas reinhardtii*, while not an embryophyte itself, contains a green-pigmented chloroplast related to that of land plants, making it useful for study.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] A red alga, *Cyanidioschyzon merolae*, has also been used to study some basic chloroplast functions.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Spinach, peas, soybeans and a moss *Physcomitrella patens* are commonly used to study plant cell biology.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Epigenetics is the study of heritable changes in gene function that cannot be explained by changes in the underlying DNA sequence but cause the organism's genes to behave (or "express themselves") differently.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] One example of epigenetic change is the marking of the genes by DNA methylation which determines whether they will be expressed or not.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Gene expression can also be controlled by repressor proteins that attach to silencer regions of the DNA and prevent that region of the DNA code from being expressed.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Epigenetic marks may be added or removed from the DNA during programmed stages of development of the plant, and are responsible, for example, for the differences between anthers, petals and normal leaves, despite the fact that they all have the same underlying genetic code.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Epigenetic changes may be temporary or may remain through successive cell divisions for the remainder of the cell's life.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Some epigenetic changes have been shown to be heritable, while others are reset in the germ cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Epigenetic changes in eukaryotic biology serve to regulate the process of cellular differentiation.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] During morphogenesis, totipotent stem cells become the various pluripotent cell lines of the embryo, which in turn become fully differentiated cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] A single fertilised egg cell, the zygote, gives rise to the many different plant cell types including parenchyma, xylem vessel elements, phloem sieve tubes, guard cells of the epidermis, etc. as it continues to divide.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The process results from the epigenetic activation of some genes and inhibition of others.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Unlike animals, many plant cells, particularly those of the parenchyma, do not terminally differentiate, remaining totipotent with the ability to give rise to a new individual plant.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Exceptions include highly lignified cells, the sclerenchyma and xylem which are dead at maturity, and the phloem sieve tubes which lack nuclei.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] While plants use many of the same epigenetic mechanisms as animals, such as chromatin remodelling, an alternative hypothesis is that plants set their gene expression patterns using positional information from the environment and surrounding cells to determine their developmental fate.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Epigenetic changes can lead to paramutations, which do not follow the Mendelian heritage rules.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] These epigenetic marks are carried from one generation to the next, with one allele inducing a change on the other.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The algae are a polyphyletic group and are placed in various divisions, some more closely related to plants than others.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] There are many differences between them in features such as cell wall composition, biochemistry, pigmentation, chloroplast structure and nutrient reserves.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The algal division Charophyta, sister to the green algal division Chlorophyta, is considered to contain the ancestor of true plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The Charophyte class Charophyceae and the land plant sub-kingdom Embryophyta together form the monophyletic group or clade Streptophytina.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Nonvascular land plants are embryophytes that lack the vascular tissues xylem and phloem.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] They include mosses, liverworts and hornworts.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Pteridophytic vascular plants with true xylem and phloem that reproduced by spores germinating into free-living gametophytes evolved during the Silurian period and diversified into several lineages during the late Silurian and early Devonian.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Representatives of the lycopods have survived to the present day.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] By the end of the Devonian period, several groups, including the lycopods, sphenophylls and progymnosperms, had independently evolved "megaspory" – their spores were of two distinct sizes, larger megaspores and smaller microspores.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Their reduced gametophytes developed from megaspores retained within the spore-producing organs (megasporangia) of the sporophyte, a condition known as endospory.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Seeds consist of an endosporic megasporangium surrounded by one or two sheathing layers (integuments).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The young sporophyte develops within the seed, which on germination splits to release it.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] The earliest known seed plants date from the latest Devonian Famennian stage.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Following the evolution of the seed habit, seed plants diversified, giving rise to a number of now-extinct groups, including seed ferns, as well as the modern gymnosperms and angiosperms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Gymnosperms produce "naked seeds" not fully enclosed in an ovary; modern representatives include conifers, cycads, *Ginkgo*, and Gnetales.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Angiosperms produce seeds enclosed in a structure such as a carpel or an ovary.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p01] Ongoing research on the molecular phylogenetics of living plants appears to show that the angiosperms are a sister clade to the gymnosperms.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Plant physiology encompasses all the internal chemical and physical activities of plants associated with life.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Chemicals obtained from the air, soil and water form the basis of all plant metabolism.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The energy of sunlight, captured by oxygenic photosynthesis and released by cellular respiration, is the basis of almost all life.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Photoautotrophs, including all green plants, algae and cyanobacteria gather energy directly from sunlight by photosynthesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Heterotrophs including all animals, all fungi, all completely parasitic plants, and non-photosynthetic bacteria take in organic molecules produced by photoautotrophs and respire them or use them in the construction of cells and tissues.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Respiration is the oxidation of carbon compounds by breaking them down into simpler structures to release the energy they contain, essentially the opposite of photosynthesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Molecules are moved within plants by transport processes that operate at a variety of spatial scales.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Subcellular transport of ions, electrons and molecules such as water and enzymes occurs across cell membranes.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Minerals and water are transported from roots to other parts of the plant in the transpiration stream.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Diffusion, osmosis, and active transport and mass flow are all different ways transport can occur.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Examples of elements that plants need to transport are nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulphur.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] In vascular plants, these elements are extracted from the soil as soluble ions by the roots and transported throughout the plant in the xylem.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Most of the elements required for plant nutrition come from the chemical breakdown of soil minerals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Sucrose produced by photosynthesis is transported from the leaves to other parts of the plant in the phloem and plant hormones are transported by a variety of processes.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Plants are not passive, but respond to external signals such as light, touch, and injury by moving or growing towards or away from the stimulus, as appropriate.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Tangible evidence of touch sensitivity is the almost instantaneous collapse of leaflets of *Mimosa pudica*, the insect traps of Venus flytrap and bladderworts, and the pollinia of orchids.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The hypothesis that plant growth and development is coordinated by plant hormones or plant growth regulators first emerged in the late 19th century.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Darwin experimented on the movements of plant shoots and roots towards light and gravity, and concluded "It is hardly an exaggeration to say that the tip of the radicle . . acts like the brain of one of the lower animals . . directing the several movements".
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] About the same time, the role of auxins (from the Greek *auxein*, to grow) in control of plant growth was first outlined by the Dutch scientist Frits Went.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The first known auxin, indole-3-acetic acid (IAA), which promotes cell growth, was only isolated from plants about 50 years later.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] This compound mediates the tropic responses of shoots and roots towards light and gravity.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Cytokinins are a class of plant hormones named for their control of cell division (especially cytokinesis).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The natural cytokinin zeatin was discovered in corn, *Zea mays*, and is a derivative of the purine adenine.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Zeatin is produced in roots and transported to shoots in the xylem where it promotes cell division, bud development, and the greening of chloroplasts.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The gibberelins, such as gibberelic acid are diterpenes synthesised from acetyl CoA via the mevalonate pathway.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] They are involved in the promotion of germination and dormancy-breaking in seeds, in regulation of plant height by controlling stem elongation and the control of flowering.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Abscisic acid (ABA) occurs in all land plants except liverworts, and is synthesised from carotenoids in the chloroplasts and other plastids.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] It inhibits cell division, promotes seed maturation, and dormancy, and promotes stomatal closure.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] It was so named because it was originally thought to control abscission.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Ethylene is a gaseous hormone that is produced in all higher plant tissues from methionine.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] It is now known to be the hormone that stimulates or regulates fruit ripening and abscission, and it, or the synthetic growth regulator ethephon which is rapidly metabolised to produce ethylene, are used on industrial scale to promote ripening of cotton, pineapples and other climacteric crops.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Another class of phytohormones is the jasmonates, first isolated from the oil of *Jasminum grandiflorum* which regulates wound responses in plants by unblocking the expression of genes required in the systemic acquired resistance response to pathogen attack.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] In addition to being the primary energy source for plants, light functions as a signalling device, providing information to the plant, such as how much sunlight the plant receives each day.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] This can result in adaptive changes in a process known as photomorphogenesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Phytochromes are the photoreceptors in a plant that are sensitive to light.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Plant anatomy is the study of the structure of plant cells and tissues, whereas plant morphology is the study of their external form.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] All plants are multicellular eukaryotes, their DNA stored in nuclei.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Other plastids contain storage products such as starch (amyloplasts) or lipids (elaioplasts).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Uniquely, streptophyte cells and those of the green algal order Trentepohliales divide by construction of a phragmoplast as a template for building a cell plate late in cell division.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] , the most common type of plant (three-fifths of all plant species).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] However, no plant actually looks exactly like this.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The bodies of vascular plants including clubmosses, ferns and seed plants (gymnosperms and angiosperms) generally have aerial and subterranean subsystems.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The shoots consist of stems bearing green photosynthesising leaves and reproductive structures.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The underground vascularised roots bear root hairs at their tips and generally lack chlorophyll.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Non-vascular plants, the liverworts, hornworts and mosses do not produce ground-penetrating vascular roots and most of the plant participates in photosynthesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The sporophyte generation is nonphotosynthetic in liverworts but may be able to contribute part of its energy needs by photosynthesis in mosses and hornworts.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The root system and the shoot system are interdependent – the usually nonphotosynthetic root system depends on the shoot system for food, and the usually photosynthetic shoot system depends on water and minerals from the root system.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Cells in each system are capable of creating cells of the other and producing adventitious shoots or roots.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Stolons and tubers are examples of shoots that can grow roots.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Roots that spread out close to the surface, such as those of willows, can produce shoots and ultimately new plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] In the event that one of the systems is lost, the other can often regrow it.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] In fact it is possible to grow an entire plant from a single leaf, as is the case with plants in *Streptocarpus* sect.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] *Saintpaulia*, or even a single cell – which can dedifferentiate into a callus (a mass of unspecialised cells) that can grow into a new plant.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] In vascular plants, the xylem and phloem are the conductive tissues that transport resources between shoots and roots.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Roots are often adapted to store food such as sugars or starch, as in sugar beets and carrots.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Stems mainly provide support to the leaves and reproductive structures, but can store water in succulent plants such as cacti, food as in potato tubers, or reproduce vegetatively as in the stolons of strawberry plants or in the process of layering.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Leaves gather sunlight and carry out photosynthesis.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Large, flat, flexible, green leaves are called foliage leaves.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Gymnosperms, such as conifers, cycads, *Ginkgo*, and gnetophytes are seed-producing plants with open seeds.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Angiosperms are seed-producing plants that produce flowers and have enclosed seeds.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Woody plants, such as azaleas and oaks, undergo a secondary growth phase resulting in two additional types of tissues: wood (secondary xylem) and bark (secondary phloem and cork).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] All gymnosperms and many angiosperms are woody plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Some plants reproduce sexually, some asexually, and some via both means.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Although reference to major morphological categories such as root, stem, leaf, and trichome are useful, one has to keep in mind that these categories are linked through intermediate forms so that a continuum between the categories results.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Furthermore, structures can be seen as processes, that is, process combinations.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Systematic botany is part of systematic biology, which is concerned with the range and diversity of organisms and their relationships, particularly as determined by their evolutionary history.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] It involves, or is related to, biological classification, scientific taxonomy and phylogenetics.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Biological classification is the method by which botanists group organisms into categories such as genera or species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Biological classification is a form of scientific taxonomy.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Modern taxonomy is rooted in the work of Carl Linnaeus, who grouped species according to shared physical characteristics.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] These groupings have since been revised to align better with the Darwinian principle of common descent – grouping organisms by ancestry rather than superficial characteristics.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] While scientists do not always agree on how to classify organisms, molecular phylogenetics, which uses DNA sequences as data, has driven many recent revisions along evolutionary lines and is likely to continue to do so.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The dominant classification system is called Linnaean taxonomy.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] It includes ranks and binomial nomenclature.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The nomenclature of botanical organisms is codified in the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (ICN) and administered by the International Botanical Congress.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Kingdom Plantae belongs to Domain Eukaryota and is broken down recursively until each species is separately classified.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The order is: Kingdom; Phylum (or Division); Class; Order; Family; Genus (plural *genera*); Species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The scientific name of a plant represents its genus and its species within the genus, resulting in a single worldwide name for each organism.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] For example, the tiger lily is *Lilium columbianum*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] *Lilium* is the genus, and *columbianum* the specific epithet.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The combination is the name of the species.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] When writing the scientific name of an organism, it is proper to capitalise the first letter in the genus and put all of the specific epithet in lowercase.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Additionally, the entire term is ordinarily italicised (or underlined when italics are not available).
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The evolutionary relationships and heredity of a group of organisms is called its phylogeny.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Phylogenetic studies attempt to discover phylogenies.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The basic approach is to use similarities based on shared inheritance to determine relationships.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] As an example, species of *Pereskia* are trees or bushes with prominent leaves.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] They do not obviously resemble a typical leafless cactus such as an *Echinocactus*.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] However, both *Pereskia* and *Echinocactus* have spines produced from areoles (highly specialised pad-like structures) suggesting that the two genera are indeed related.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Judging relationships based on shared characters requires care, since plants may resemble one another through convergent evolution in which characters have arisen independently.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Some euphorbias have leafless, rounded bodies adapted to water conservation similar to those of globular cacti, but characters such as the structure of their flowers make it clear that the two groups are not closely related.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Only derived characters, such as the spine-producing areoles of cacti, provide evidence for descent from a common ancestor.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The results of cladistic analyses are expressed as cladograms: tree-like diagrams showing the pattern of evolutionary branching and descent.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] From the 1990s onwards, the predominant approach to constructing phylogenies for living plants has been molecular phylogenetics, which uses molecular characters, particularly DNA sequences, rather than morphological characters like the presence or absence of spines and areoles.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] The difference is that the genetic code itself is used to decide evolutionary relationships, instead of being used indirectly via the characters it gives rise to.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Clive Stace describes this as having "direct access to the genetic basis of evolution." As a simple example, prior to the use of genetic evidence, fungi were thought either to be plants or to be more closely related to plants than animals.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Genetic evidence suggests that the true evolutionary relationship of multicelled organisms is as shown in the cladogram below – fungi are more closely related to animals than to plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] In 1998, the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group published a phylogeny for flowering plants based on an analysis of DNA sequences from most families of flowering plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] As a result of this work, many questions, such as which families represent the earliest branches of angiosperms, have now been answered.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Investigating how plant species are related to each other allows botanists to better understand the process of evolution in plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Despite the study of model plants and increasing use of DNA evidence, there is ongoing work and discussion among taxonomists about how best to classify plants into various taxa.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] Technological developments such as computers and electron microscopes have greatly increased the level of detail studied and speed at which data can be analysed.
[src:alan-mchughen/botany-p02] A few symbols are in current use in botany.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The institution was established as Dalhousie College, a nonsectarian institution established in 1818 by the eponymous Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia, George Ramsay, 9th Earl of Dalhousie, with education reformer Thomas McCulloch as its first principal.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] However, the college did not hold its first class until 1838, with operations remaining sporadic due to financial difficulties.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The college was reorganized in 1863 and renamed The Governors of Dalhousie College and University.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university formally changed its name to Dalhousie University in 1997 through the same provincial legislation that merged the institution with the Technical University of Nova Scotia.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie's varsity teams, the Tigers, compete in the Atlantic University Sport conference of Canadian Interuniversity Sport.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie's Faculty of Agriculture varsity teams are called the Dalhousie Rams, and compete in the ACAA and CCAA.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie is a coeducational university with more than 20,000 students and 150,000 alumni around the world.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university's notable alumni include a Nobel Prize winner and 94 Rhodes Scholars.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie was founded, as the Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia George Ramsay, 9th Earl of Dalhousie, desired a non-denominational college in Halifax.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Financing largely came from customs duties collected by a previous Lieutenant Governor, John Coape Sherbrooke, during the War of 1812 occupation of Castine, Maine; Sherbrooke invested £7,000 as an initial endowment and reserved £3,000 for the physical construction of the college.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The college was established in 1818 though it faltered shortly after, as Ramsay left Halifax to serve as the Governor General of British North America.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The school was structured upon the principles of the University of Edinburgh, located near Ramsay's home in Scotland, where lectures were open to male students, regardless of Christian religion or nationality.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1821, Dalhousie College was officially incorporated by the Nova Scotia House of Assembly under the 1821 Act of Incorporation.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The college did not hold its first class until 1838; operation of the college was intermittent and no degrees were awarded.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1841, an Act of the Nova Scotia House of Assembly conferred university powers on Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie's first principal was Thomas McCulloch.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1838, the board of Dalhousie College was able to convince McCulloch leave Pictou Academy and take on the floundering Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Following McCulloch's death, the college fell into decline once again and was reorganized as a high school in 1848.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1863, the college opened for a third time and was reorganized by another legislative act, which added "University" to the school's name: "The Governors of Dalhousie College and University".
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie reopened with six professors and one tutor.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] When it awarded its first degrees in 1866, the student body consisted of 28 male students working toward degrees and 28 occasional students.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Despite the reorganization and an increase in students, money continued to be a problem for the institution.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1879, amid talks of closure due to the university's dire financial situation, George Munro, a wealthy New York publisher with Nova Scotian roots, began to donate to the university; Munro was brother-in-law to Dalhousie's Board of Governors member John Forrest.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] As such, Munro is credited with rescuing Dalhousie from closure.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In honour of his contributions, Dalhousie observes a university holiday called George Munro Day on the first Friday of each February.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The first female graduate was Margaret Florence Newcombe from Grafton, Nova Scotia, who earned a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1885.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Originally located at the space now occupied by Halifax City Hall, the college moved in 1886 to Carleton Campus and spread gradually to Studley Campus.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie grew steadily during the 20th century.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] From 1889 to 1962 the Halifax Conservatory was affiliated with and awarded degrees through Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1920, several buildings were destroyed by fire on the campus of the University of King's College in Windsor, Nova Scotia.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Through a grant from the Carnegie Foundation, King's College relocated to Halifax and entered into a partnership with Dalhousie that continues to this day.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie expanded on 1 April 1997 when provincial legislation mandated an amalgamation with the nearby Technical University of Nova Scotia.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] This merger saw reorganization of faculties and departments to create the Faculty of Engineering, Faculty of Computer Science and the Faculty of Architecture and Planning.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] From 1997 to 2000, the Technical University of Nova Scotia operated as a constituent college of Dalhousie called Dalhousie Polytechnic of Nova Scotia (DalTech) until the collegiate system was dissolved.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The legislation that merged the two schools also formally changed the name of the institution to its present form, Dalhousie University.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] On 1 September 2012, the Nova Scotia Agricultural College merged into Dalhousie to form a new Faculty of Agriculture, located in Bible Hill, Nova Scotia.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie has three campuses within the Halifax Peninsula and a fourth, the Agricultural Campus, in Bible Hill, Nova Scotia.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Studley Campus in Halifax serves as the primary campus; it houses the majority of the university's academic buildings such as faculties, athletic facilities, and the university's Student Union Building.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The campus is largely surrounded by residential neighbourhoods.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Robie Street divides it from the adjacent Carleton Campus, which houses the faculties of dentistry, medicine, and other health profession departments.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The campus is adjacent to two large teaching hospitals affiliated with the school: the IWK Health Centre and the Queen Elizabeth II Health Sciences Centre.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Sexton Campus in Downtown Halifax hosts the engineering, architecture and planning faculties.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Sexton Campus served as the campus of the Technical University of Nova Scotia prior to amalgamation.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Agricultural Campus in Bible Hill, a suburban community of Truro, served as the campus for the Nova Scotia Agricultural College prior to its merger with Dalhousie in 2011.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university presently operates the largest academic library system in Atlantic Canada, and hosts the headquarters for the Ocean Tracking Network.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The buildings at Dalhousie vary in age from Hart House, which was completed in 1864, to the Collaborative Health Education Building, completed in 2015.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The original building of Dalhousie University was completed in 1824 on Halifax's Grand Parade.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] It was demolished in 1885 when the university outgrew the premises, and the City of Halifax sought possession of the entire Grand Parade.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Halifax City Hall presently occupies the site of the original Dalhousie College.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The largest, Killam Memorial Library, opened in 1971 and claims to be the largest academic library in Atlantic Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Kellogg Health Science Library provides services largely for the faculties of dentistry, medicine, and other health professions.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Sexton Design & Technology Library is located within Sexton Campus.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Its collection largely serves those in the faculties of engineering, architecture and planning, and houses the university's rare books collection.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Sir James Dunn Law Library holds the university's collection of common law materials, legal periodicals, as well as books on international law, health law, and environmental law.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] MacRae Library is located at the university's Agricultural Campus, and has the largest collection of agricultural resource material in Atlantic Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Dalhousie University Archives houses official records of, or relating to, or people/activities connected with Dalhousie University and its founding institutions.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The archives also houses material related to theatre, business and labour in Nova Scotia.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The collection consists of manuscripts, texts, photographs, audio-visual material, microfilm, music, and artifacts.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university's first library, Macdonald Memorial Library, was built after alumni raised funds on the death of professor Charles Macdonald, who had left the university $2,000 to buy books in English literature on his death in 1901.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The biology department operates the Thomas McCulloch Museum in its Life Sciences Centre (LSC).
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The most notable of the museum's exhibits include its preserved birds collection.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Other collections include its Lorenzen ceramic mushrooms, its coral and shell collection, and its butterfly and insect collection.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The museum's namesake Thomas McCulloch was a Scottish Presbyterian minister who served as Dalhousie's first president and created the Audubon mounted bird collection which is now housed at the museum.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Dalhousie Art Gallery is both a public gallery and an academic support unit housed since 1971 on the lowest level of the Dalhousie Arts Centre.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] It is host to a permanent collection of over 1000 works.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Some of the outdoor sculptures around the campus are part of this collection, such as the distinctive *Marine Venus* which has sat in the median of University Avenue since 1969.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] A notable exhibition from the Dalhousie Art Gallery includes "Archives of the Future" (March – April 2016) exploring the relationship between art creation and commerce with work by artists Zachary Gough, Dawn Georg, Sharlene Bamboat, Katie Vida and Dana Claxton.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie University is actively involved in sustainability issues and has received a number of sustainability awards and recognition for academic programs, university operations, and research.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2022, Dalhousie received a GOLD rating from AASHE STARS (Version 2.2).
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2009, the university signed the University and College Presidents' Climate Change Statement of Action for Canada to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie is also a signatory of UNEP's International Declaration on Cleaner Production.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 1999, the university signed the Talloires Declaration, which committed Dalhousie and other higher education institutions to developing, creating, supporting, and maintaining sustainability.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] University governance is conducted through the Board of Governors and the Senate, both of which were given much of their present power in the Unofficial Consolidation of an Act for the Regulation and Support of Dalhousie College in Chapter 24 of the Acts of 1863.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] This statute replaced ones from 1820, 1823, 1838, 1841 and 1848, and has since been supplemented 11 times, most recently in 1995.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Board is responsible for conduct, management, and control of the university and of its property, revenues, business, and affairs.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Board members, known as Governors of the Board, include the university's chancellor, president, and 25 other members.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Members include people from within the university community such as four approved representatives from Dalhousie Student Union, and those in the surrounding community, such as the Mayor of Halifax.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Senate is responsible for the university's academics, including standards for admission and qualifications for degrees, diplomas, and certificates.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Senate consists of 73 positions granted to the various faculty representatives, academic administrators, and student representatives.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The president acts as the chief executive officer and is responsible to the Board of Governors and to the Senate for the supervision of administrative and academic works.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Thomas McCulloch served as the first president when the office was created in 1838.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] John Forrest was the longest-serving president, holding the office from 1885 to 1911.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Kim Brooks is the 13th president of the university, and has served since August 2023.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In August 2025, under the leadership of President Brooks, the university took the unprecedented action of locking out approximately 1000 members of the Dalhousie Faculty Association.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The contract dispute primarily focused on Dalhousie's use of non permanent contracts, creating precocity amongst certain faulty and cost of living salary increases.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The lock out lasted one month, and despite demands from the student union, no refunds were given to students who missed class time.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] It also had negative impacts on research as locked out faculty had no ability to complete work or apply for grants.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] University of King's College is a post-secondary institution in Halifax affiliated with Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The institution's campus is located adjacent to Dalhousie's Studley campus.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Established in 1789, it was the first post-secondary institution in English Canada and the oldest English-speaking Commonwealth university outside the United Kingdom.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The University of King's College was formerly an independent institution located in Windsor, Nova Scotia, until 1920, when a fire ravaged its campus.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] To continue operation, the University of King's College accepted a generous grant from the Carnegie Foundation, although the terms of the grant required that it move to Halifax and enter into association with Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Under the agreement, King's agreed to pay the salaries of a number of Dalhousie professors, who in turn were to help in the management and academic life of the college.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Students at King's have access to all of the amenities at Dalhousie, and academic programs at King's would fold into the College of Arts and Sciences at Dalhousie according to the agreement.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Presently, students of both institutions are allowed to switch between the two throughout their enrolment.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In spite of the shared academic programs and facilities, the University of King's College maintains its own scholarships, bursaries, athletics programs, and student residences.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university completed the 2017–18 year with revenues of $697.354 million and expenses of $664.274 million, yielding a surplus of $33.08 million.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The largest source of revenue for the university was provincial operational grants, followed by tuition fees.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The total endowment revenue reported in fiscal 2017–2018 was $481.372 million.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In August 2025, the university became the first U15 institution in Canada to initiate a lockout against their faculty labour union, several days before the union was able to complete their vote on the university's final offer.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university claimed that they did not have the financial capacity to have their wages keep up with inflation; whereas the union claimed that the university favoured spending on infrastructure such as a new sports arena over paying their employees a fair wage.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] At the end of a one month lock-out, Dalhousie paid out nearly twice what they claimed they could initially afford.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The student union issued calls for tuition to be returned due to the unnecessary labour tactic used by president Kim Brooks and her Board of Governors.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The lockout also sparked criticism about the university's paid participation with Nous Data Insights, an Australian based consulting firm which has been known for making cuts to the academic side of universities in favour of profit.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] There have been several Dalhousie University scandals related to discrimination at the university.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In reaction to this, the university has initiated recruitment strategies to increase the representation of under-represented groups at Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie is a publicly funded research university, and a member of the Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada, as well as the U15.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] As of 2022, there were 20,970 students enrolled at the university.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie offers more than 4,000 courses and over 200 degree programs in 13 undergraduate, graduate, and professional faculties.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The requirements for admission differ between students from Nova Scotia, students from other provinces in Canada, and international students due to lack of uniformity in marking schemes.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The requirements for admission also differ depending on the program.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2011, the secondary school average for incoming first-year undergraduate students was 85 per cent.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Canadian students may apply for financial aid such as the Nova Scotia Student Assistance Program and Canada Student Loans and Grants through the federal and provincial governments.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Financial aid may also be provided in the form of loans, grants, bursaries, scholarships, fellowships, debt reduction, interest relief, and work programs.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university's registrar provides scholarships for its students in order to provide financial assistance, or to reward academic merits or performances in another fields, such as community involvement and leadership.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The 2025 Academic Ranking of World Universities ranked Dalhousie University 301–400 in the world and 11–15 in Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The 2025 QS World University Rankings ranked the university 275th in the world, and twelfth in Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The 2025 Times Higher Education World University Rankings placed Dalhousie 301–350 in the world.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] News & World Report Best Global University Ranking*, the university placed 385th in the world, and 11th in Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In terms of national rankings, *Maclean's* ranked Dalhousie ninth in their 2026 Medical-Doctoral university rankings.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie was ranked in spite of having opted out – along with several other universities in Canada – of participating in Maclean's graduate survey since 2006.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie also placed in rankings that evaluated the employment prospects of its graduates.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In QS's 2022 graduate employability ranking, the university ranked 301–500 in the world, and 9–17 in Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2018, Research Infosource ranked Dalhousie as 15th on their list for top 50 research universities in Canada, with a sponsored research income (external sources of funding) of $150.038 million in 2017.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In the same year, Dalhousie's faculty averaged a sponsored research income of $130,000, while its graduate students averaged a sponsored research income of $44,600.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2003 and 2004, *The Scientist* placed Dalhousie among the top five places in the world outside the United States for postdoctoral work and conducting scientific research.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2007 Dalhousie topped the list of *The Scientist'*s "Best Places to Work in Academia".
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The annual list divides research and academic institutions into American and international lists; Dalhousie University ranked first in the international category.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] According to a survey conducted by *The Scientist*, Dalhousie was the best non-commercial scientific institute in which to work in Canada.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie's research performance has been noted in several bibliometric university rankings, which use citation analysis to evaluate the impact a university has on academic publications.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Marine research at Dalhousie has become a large focus of the university, with many of the university's faculty members involved in some form of marine research.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Notably, Dalhousie is the headquarters of the Ocean Tracking Network, a research effort using implanted acoustic transmitters to study fish migration patterns.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie houses a number of marine research pools, a wet laboratory, and a benthic flume, which are collectively known as the Aquatron laboratory.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie is one of the founding members of the Halifax Marine Research Institute, founded on 2 June 2011.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The institute, which is a partnership between a number of private industries, government, and post-secondary institutions, was designed to help increase the scale, quality, internationalization and impact of marine research in the region.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2011, the university, along with WWF-Canada, created the Conservation Legacy For Oceans, which aimed at providing scholarships, funding, curriculum development, and work placements for students and academics dedicated to marine research, law, management, and policy making.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2016, Dalhousie partnered with Memorial University of Newfoundland and the University of Prince Edward Island to form a collaborative research organization known as The Ocean Frontier Institute.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Many of Dalhousie's faculties and departments focus on marine research.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Faculty of Engineering operates the Ocean Research Centre Atlantic, which is dedicated to research and tests in naval and off-shore engineering.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Schulich School of Law also operates the Marine & Environmental Law Institute, which carries out research and conducts consultancy activities for governmental and non-governmental organizations.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The school's Department of Political Science similarly operates the Centre for Foreign Policy Studies, which is primarily concerned with the fields of Canadian and American foreign, security, and defence policy, including maritime security policy.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The student body of Dalhousie is currently represented by two student unions; the Dalhousie Student Union, which represents the general student population, and the Dalhousie Association for Graduate Students, which represents the interests of graduate students specifically.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] As of 2011, there were three sororities and three fraternities.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] They operate as non-accredited organizations and are not recognized by the Dalhousie Student Union.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The main student newspaper, *The Dalhousie Gazette*, claims to be the oldest student-run newspaper in North America.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The newspaper's offices are in the Student Union building.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The radio station began as a radio club in 1964 and operated as CKDU in 1975; it began FM broadcasting in 1985.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] CKDU acquired its present frequency 88.1 in 2006 and upgraded its transmitting power.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In 2021 and 2022, controversies arose around alcohol consumption at unsanctioned student gatherings on campus, specifically 'homecoming' in early October.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Halifax Police urged the university to play a more active role in the issue.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] In addition to the efforts made by the Dalhousie Student Union (DSU) Council, Dalhousie students have created and participated in over 320 clubs/societies.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Management Society, for example, is a group of students in the Faculty of Management who group together to enhance the experience of students in that faculty by hosting events, providing assistance and giving back.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Until 25 July 2016, Dalhousie offered a website named "Tiger Society" which listed all current clubs and societies that were available for students to join.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Through this website, students could request to join a society.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie also holds a Society Fair at the beginning of each fall and winter semester, in which all societies are given the opportunity to display their purpose/efforts and recruit new members.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Student societies partake in a range of activities from simple gatherings, study groups, bake sales, intramural sports teams, to organizing larger scale fundraising events.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie's sports teams are called the Tigers.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Tigers varsity teams participate primarily in the Atlantic University Sport (AUS) of U Sports.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] There are teams for basketball, hockey, soccer, swimming, track and field, cross country running, and volleyball.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Tigers garnered a number of championships in the first decade of the 20th century, winning 63 AUS championships and two U Sports championships.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] More than 2,500 students participate in competitive clubs, intramural sport leagues, and tournaments.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Opportunities are offered at multiple skill levels across a variety of sports.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie has six competitive sports clubs and 17 recreational clubs.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie's Agricultural Campus operates its own varsity team, called the Dalhousie Rams.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Rams varsity team participates in the Atlantic Collegiate Athletic Association, a member of the Canadian Collegiate Athletic Association.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The Rams varsity teams include badminton, basketball, rugby, soccer, volleyball, and woodsmen.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The seal of the University is based on the heraldic achievement of Clan Ramsay of Scotland, of which founder George Ramsay was clan head.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The heraldic achievement consists of five parts – shield, coronet, crest, supporters and motto.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] One major difference between the Ramsay achievement and the achievement on the seal is that the Ramsay achievement features a griffin and greyhound, whereas the seal has two dragons supporting the eagle-adorned shield.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Initially, the Ramsay achievement was used to identify Dalhousie, but the seal has evolved with the amalgamations the university has undergone.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The shield used by the university was originally silver-coloured, as the Ramsay arms are, but in 1950 the university's Board of Governors changed it to gold to match the university's colours of gold and black.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] These colours were adopted in 1887, after the rugby team led the debate about college colours for football jerseys.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The shield seen on Dalhousie's seal has been used as the logo since 1987, with the present incarnation in use since 2022.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The university motto *Ora et Labora* translates from Latin as "pray and work"; it adopted in 1870 from the Earl of Dalhousie's motto to replace the university's original one, which the administration believed did not convey confidence.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The original motto was *Forsan* (Latin for "perhaps"), and first appeared in the first *Dalhousie Gazette* of 1869.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Among the school's songs is the "Carmina Dalhousiana", written in Halifax in 1882.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] A Dalhousie University songbook was compiled by Charles B.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie graduates have found success in a variety of fields, serving as heads of a diverse array of public and private institutions.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie University has over 130,000 alumni.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Throughout Dalhousie's history, faculty, alumni, and former students have played prominent roles in many fields, and include 91 Rhodes Scholars.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Dalhousie has also educated Nobel laureates.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Astrophysicist and Dalhousie alumni Arthur B.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] McDonald (BSc 1964, MSc 1965) received the 2015 Nobel Prize in Physics for identifying neutrino change identities and mass.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] McDonald was also previously awarded the Herzberg Prize and the Benjamin Franklin Prize in physics.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Other notable graduates of Dalhousie includes Donald O.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Hebb, who helped advance the field of neuropsychology, Kathryn D.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Sullivan, the first American woman to walk in space and Jeff Dahn, one of the world's foremost researchers in lithium battery chemistry and aging.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Elizabeth Patton, elected as a Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh (2021) and Personal Chair in Melanoma Genetics and Drug Discovery, MRC Human Genetics Unit, Edinburgh.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Notable politicians who have attended Dalhousie include three Prime Ministers of Canada, R.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Eight graduates have served as Lieutenant Governors: John Crosbie, Myra Freeman, Clarence Gosse, John Keiller MacKay, Henry Poole MacKeen, John Robert Nicholson, Fabian O'Dea, and Albert Walsh.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Thirteen graduates have served as provincial premiers: Allan Blakeney, John Buchanan, Alex Campbell, Amor De Cosmos, Darrell Dexter, David Eby, Joe Ghiz, John Hamm, Angus Lewis Macdonald, Russell MacLellan, Gerald Regan, Robert Stanfield, Clyde Wells, and Danny Williams.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] The first woman appointed to the Supreme Court of Canada, Bertha Wilson, was a graduate from Dalhousie Law School.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Other notable alumni from the Dalhousie include Lucy Maud Montgomery, an author that wrote a series of novels, including *Anne of Green Gables*.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Prominent business leaders who studied at Dalhousie include Jamie Baillie, former CEO of Credit Union Atlantic, Graham Day, former CEO of British Shipbuilders,Sean Durfy, former CEO of WestJet, and Charles Peter McColough, former president and CEO of Xerox.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Redmond College, attended by Anne Shirley in L.M.
[src:alan-mchughen/dalhousie-university] Montgomery's *Anne of the Island*, is based on Dalhousie.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The **Executive Office of the President of the United States** (**EOP**) comprises the offices and agencies that support the work of the president at the center of the executive branch of the United States federal government.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The office consists of several offices and agencies, such as the White House Office (the staff working closest with the president, including West Wing staff), the National Security Council, Homeland Security Council, Office of Management and Budget, Council of Economic Advisers, and others.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The Eisenhower Executive Office Building houses most staff.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The office is also referred to as a "permanent government", since many policy programs, and the people who are charged with implementing them, continue between presidential administrations.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The civil servants who work in the Executive Office of the President are regarded as nonpartisan and politically neutral, so they are capable of providing objective and impartial advice.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] With the increase in technological and global advancement, the size of the White House staff has increased to include an array of policy experts responsible with managing various federal governmental functions and policy areas.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] As of 2015, it included approximately 1,800 positions, most of which did not require confirmation from the U.S.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The office is overseen by the White House chief of staff.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Since January 20, 2025, that position has been held by Susie Wiles, who was appointed by President Donald Trump.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] She is the first woman to hold the title.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] In 1937, the Brownlow Committee, which was a presidentially commissioned panel of political science and public administration experts, recommended sweeping changes to the executive branch of the U.S. federal government, including the creation of the Executive Office of the President.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Based on these recommendations, President Franklin D.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Roosevelt in 1939 lobbied Congress to approve the Reorganization Act of 1939.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] 1, which created the office, which reported directly to the president.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The office encompassed two subunits at its outset, the White House Office (WHO) and the Bureau of the Budget, the predecessor to today's Office of Management and Budget, which was created in 1921 and originally located in the Treasury Department.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] It absorbed most of the functions of the National Emergency Council.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Initially, the new staff system appeared more ambitious on paper than in practice; the increase in the size of the staff was quite modest at the start.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] However, it laid the groundwork for the large and organizationally complex White House staff that emerged during the presidencies of Roosevelt's successors.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Roosevelt's efforts are also notable in contrast to those of his predecessors in office.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] During the 19th century, presidents had few staff resources.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Thomas Jefferson had one messenger and one secretary at his disposal, both of whose salaries were paid by the president personally.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] It was not until 1857 that Congress appropriated money ($2,500) for the hiring of one clerk.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Grant's presidency (1869–1877), the staff had grown to three.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] By 1900, the White House staff included one "secretary to the president" (then the title of the president's chief aide), two assistant secretaries, two executive clerks, a stenographer, and seven other office personnel.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Harding, there were thirty-one staff, although most were in clerical positions.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] During Herbert Hoover's presidency, two additional secretaries to the president were added by Congress, one of whom Hoover designated as his press secretary.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] After World War II, in particular, during the Eisenhower presidency, the staff was expanded and reorganized.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Army general, had been Supreme Allied Commander during the war and reorganized the Executive Office to suit his leadership style.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Estimates indicate some 3,000 to 4,000 persons serve in office staff positions with policy-making responsibilities, with a budget of $300 to $400 million (George W.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Bush's budget request for Fiscal Year 2005 was for $341 million in support of 1,850 personnel).
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Some observers have noted a problem of control for the president due to the increase in staff and departments, making coordination and cooperation between the various departments of the Executive Office more difficult.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The president had the power to reorganize the Executive Office due to the 1949 Reorganization Act which gave the president considerable discretion, until 1983 when it was renewed due to President Reagan's administration allegedly encountering "disloyalty and obstruction".
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The chief of staff is the head of the Executive Office and can therefore ultimately decide what the president needs to deal with personally and what can be dealt with by other staff.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Senior staff within the Executive Office of the President have the rank of **Assistant to the President**, second-level staff are **Deputy Assistant to the President**, and third-level staff are **Special Assistant to the President**.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The core White House staff appointments, and most Executive Office officials generally, are not required to be confirmed by the U.S.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Senate, although there are a handful of exceptions (e.g., the director of the Office of Management and Budget, the chair of the Council of Economic Advisers, and the United States Trade Representative).
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The information in the following table is current as of January 20, 2025.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Only principal executives are listed; for subordinate officers, see individual office pages.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The White House Office (including its various offices listed below) is a sub-unit of the Executive Office of the President (office).
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The various agencies of the office are listed above.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Congress as well as the president has some control over the Executive Office of the President.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Some of this authority stems from its appropriation powers given by the Constitution, such as the "power of the purse", which affects the Office of Management and Budget and the funding of the rest of federal departments and agencies.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] Congress also has the right to investigate the operation of the Executive Office, normally holding hearings bringing forward individual personnel to testify before a congressional committee.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] The Executive Office often helps with legislation by filling in specific points understood and written by experts, as Congressional legislation sometimes starts in broad terms.
[src:alan-mchughen/executive-office-of-the-president-of-the-united-states] This table specifies the budget of the Executive Office for the years 2008–2017, and the actual outlays for the years 1962–2023.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Examples of areas in which nominees may have made significant contributions are research; teaching; technology; services to professional societies; administration in academe, industry, and government; and communicating and interpreting science to the public.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association has awarded fellowships since 1874.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS publishes annual update of active Fellows list, which also provides email address to verify status of non-active Fellows.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] See also Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science for more examples.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS Fellows include Nobel Prize winners Michael W.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Young and Michael Rosbash, ACM Turing Award winner David Patterson, IEEE Medal of Honor winner Irwin M.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Jacobs, American Physical Society Fellow Natalie Roe, cancer researcher Yun Yen, and many more.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maria Elena Zavala, who is a recipient of the Presidential Award for Excellence in Science, Mathematics, and Engineering Mentoring, is also a Fellow.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other fellows includes Jiaxing Huang, and Duan Xiangfeng, a materials scientist who received the Beilby Medal and Prize in 2013.
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Starting 15 October 2018, the status of a Fellow can be revoked "in cases of proven scientific misconduct, serious breaches of professional ethics, or when the Fellow in the view of the AAAS otherwise no longer merits the status of Fellow".
[src:alan-mchughen/fellow-of-the-american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This is to limit the effects and tolerance of sexual harassment, which Margaret Hamburg, the president of the AAAS said "has no place in science".
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] An organism that is generated through genetic engineering is considered to be genetically modified (GM), and the resulting entity is a genetically modified organism (GMO).
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The first GMO was a bacterium generated by Herbert Boyer and Stanley Cohen in 1973.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Rudolf Jaenisch created the first GM animal when he inserted foreign DNA into a mouse in 1974.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The first company to focus on genetic engineering, Genentech, was founded in 1976 and began the production of human proteins.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetically engineered human insulin was produced in 1978, and insulin-producing bacteria were commercialised in 1982.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetically modified food has been sold since 1994, with the release of the Flavr Savr tomato.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The Flavr Savr was engineered to have a longer shelf life, but most current GM crops are modified to increase resistance to insects and herbicides.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] GloFish, the first GMO designed as a pet, was sold in the United States in December 2003.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2016, salmon modified with a growth hormone were sold.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has been applied in numerous fields, including research, medicine, industrial biotechnology, and agriculture.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In research, GMOs are used to study gene function and expression through loss-of-function, gain-of-function, tracking, and expression experiments.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] By knocking out genes responsible for certain conditions, it is possible to create animal model organisms of human diseases.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] As well as producing hormones, vaccines, and other drugs, genetic engineering has the potential to cure genetic diseases through gene therapy.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Chinese hamster ovary (CHO) cells are used in industrial genetic engineering.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Additionally, mRNA vaccines are made through genetic engineering to prevent infections by viruses such as COVID-19.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The same techniques that are used to produce drugs can also have industrial applications, such as producing enzymes for laundry detergent, cheeses, and other products.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The rise of commercialised genetically modified crops has provided economic benefit to farmers in many different countries; however, it has also been the source of most of the controversy surrounding the technology.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This has been present since its early use; the first field trials were destroyed by anti-GM activists.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Although there is a scientific consensus that food derived from GMO crops poses no greater risk to human health than conventional food, after testing on a case by case basis, critics consider GM food safety a leading concern.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Gene flow, impact on non-target organisms, control of the food supply, and intellectual property rights have also been raised as potential issues.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These concerns have led to the development of a regulatory framework, which started in 1975.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Eventually, this has led to a proposal of an international treaty, the Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety, which was officially adopted in 2000.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Individual countries have developed their own regulatory systems regarding GMOs, with the most marked differences occurring between the United States and Europe.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is a process that alters the genetic structure of an organism by either removing or introducing DNA or modifying existing genetic material in situ.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Unlike traditional animal and plant breeding, which involves doing multiple crosses and then selecting for the organism with the desired phenotype, genetic engineering takes the gene directly from one organism and delivers it to the other.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This is much faster, can be used to insert any genes from any organism (even ones from different domains), and prevents other undesirable genes from also being added.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering could potentially fix severe genetic disorders in humans by replacing the defective gene with a functioning one.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] It is an important tool in research that allows the function of specific genes to be studied.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Drugs, vaccines, and other products have been harvested from organisms engineered to produce them.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Crops have been developed that aid food security by increasing yield, nutritional value, and tolerance to environmental stresses.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The DNA can be introduced directly into the host organism or into a cell that is then fused or hybridised with the host.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This relies on recombinant nucleic acid techniques to form new combinations of heritable genetic material, followed by the incorporation of that material either indirectly through a vector system or directly through micro-injection, macro-injection, or micro-encapsulation.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering does not normally include traditional breeding, in vitro fertilisation, induction of polyploidy, mutagenesis, and cell fusion techniques that do not use recombinant nucleic acids or a genetically modified organism in the process.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] However, some broad definitions of genetic engineering include selective breeding.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Cloning and stem cell research, although not considered genetic engineering, are closely related, and genetic engineering can be used within them.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Synthetic biology is an emerging discipline that takes genetic engineering a step further by introducing artificially synthesised material into an organism.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Plants, animals, or microorganisms that have been changed through genetic engineering are termed genetically modified organisms or GMOs.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] If genetic material from another species is added to the host, the resulting organism is called transgenic.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] If genetic material from the same species or a species that can naturally breed with the host is used, the resulting organism is called cisgenic.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] If genetic engineering is used to remove genetic material from the target organism, the resulting organism is termed a knockout organism.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In Europe, genetic modification is synonymous with genetic engineering while within the United States of America and Canada, genetic modification can also be used to refer to more conventional breeding methods.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Humans have altered the genomes of species for thousands of years through selective breeding, or artificial selection as contrasted with natural selection.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] More recently, mutation breeding has used exposure to chemicals or radiation to produce a high frequency of random mutations for selective breeding purposes.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering, as the direct manipulation of DNA by humans outside breeding and mutations, has only existed since the 1970s.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The term "genetic engineering" was coined by the Russian-born geneticist Nikolay Timofeev-Ressovsky in his 1934 paper "The Experimental Production of Mutations", published in the British journal Biological Reviews.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Weinbaum's 1936 science fiction story *Proteus Island*.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1972, Paul Berg created the first recombinant DNA molecules by combining DNA from the monkey virus SV40 with that of the lambda virus.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1973, Herbert Boyer and Stanley Cohen created the first transgenic organism by inserting antibiotic resistance genes into the plasmid of an *Escherichia coli* bacterium.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] One of the main recommendations from this meeting was that government oversight of recombinant DNA research should be established until the technology was deemed safe.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1976, Genentech, the first genetic engineering company, was founded by Herbert Boyer and Robert Swanson and, a year later, the company produced a human protein (somatostatin) in *E. coli*.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genentech announced the production of genetically engineered human insulin in 1978.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1980, the Supreme Court of the United States in the *Diamond v.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Chakrabarty* case ruled that genetically altered life could be patented.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The insulin produced by bacteria was approved for release by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 1982.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1987, the ice-minus strain of *P. syringae* became the first genetically modified organism (GMO) to be released into the environment when a strawberry field and a potato field in California were sprayed with it.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Both test fields were attacked by activist groups the night before the tests occurred: "The world's first trial site attracted the world's first field trasher".
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The first field trials of genetically engineered plants occurred in France and the US in 1986, and tobacco plants were engineered to be resistant to herbicides.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The People's Republic of China was the first country to commercialise transgenic plants, introducing a virus-resistant tobacco in 1992.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1994, Calgene received official approval to commercially release the first genetically modified food, the Flavr Savr, a tomato engineered to have a longer shelf life.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1994, the European Union approved tobacco engineered to be resistant to the herbicide bromoxynil, making it the first genetically engineered crop commercialised in Europe.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 1995, Bt potato was approved safe by the Environmental Protection Agency, after having been approved by the FDA, making it the first pesticide-producing crop to be approved in the US.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2009, 11 transgenic crops were grown commercially in 25 countries, the largest of which by area grown were the United States, Brazil, Argentina, India, Canada, People's Republic of China, Paraguay, and South Africa.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Craig Venter Institute created the first synthetic genome and inserted it into an empty bacterial cell.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The resulting bacterium, named Mycoplasma laboratorium, could replicate and produce proteins.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Four years later, this was taken a step further when a bacterium was developed that replicated a plasmid containing a unique base pair, creating the first organism engineered to use an expanded genetic alphabet.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2012, Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier collaborated to develop the CRISPR/Cas9 system, a technique that can be used to easily and specifically alter the genome of almost any organism.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineers must first choose which gene they wish to insert into the organism.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This is driven by what the aim is for the resultant organism and is built on earlier research.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic screens can be carried out to determine potential genes, and further tests can then be used to identify the most suitable candidates.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The development of microarrays, transcriptomics, and genome sequencing has made it much easier to find suitable genes.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Luck also plays its part; the Roundup Ready gene was discovered after scientists noticed a bacterium thriving in the presence of the herbicide.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The next step is to isolate the candidate gene.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The cell containing the gene is opened, and the DNA is purified.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The gene is separated by using restriction enzymes to cut the DNA into fragments or polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to amplify up the gene segment.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These segments can then be extracted through gel electrophoresis.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] If the chosen gene or the donor organism's genome has been well studied, it may already be accessible from a genetic library.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] If the DNA sequence is known, but no copies of the gene are available, it can also be artificially synthesised.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Once isolated, the gene is ligated into a plasmid that is then inserted into a bacterium.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The plasmid is replicated when the bacteria divide, ensuring unlimited copies of the gene are available.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The RK2 plasmid is notable for its ability to replicate in a wide variety of single-celled organisms, which makes it suitable as a genetic engineering tool.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Before the gene is inserted into the target organism, it must be combined with other genetic elements.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These include a promoter and terminator region, which initiate and end transcription.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] A selectable marker gene is added, which in most cases confers antibiotic resistance, so researchers can easily determine which cells have been successfully transformed.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The gene can also be modified at this stage for better expression or effectiveness.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These manipulations are carried out using recombinant DNA techniques, such as restriction digests, ligations, and molecular cloning.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] There are a number of techniques used to insert genetic material into the host genome.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Some bacteria can naturally take up foreign DNA.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This ability can be induced in other bacteria via stress (e.g., thermal or electric shock), which increases the cell membrane's permeability to DNA; up-taken DNA can either integrate with the genome or exist as extrachromosomal DNA.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] DNA is generally inserted into animal cells using microinjection, where it can be injected through the cell's nuclear envelope directly into the nucleus, or through the use of viral vectors.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Plant genomes can be engineered by physical methods or by the use of *Agrobacterium* for the delivery of sequences hosted in T-DNA binary vectors.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In plants, the DNA is often inserted using *Agrobacterium*-mediated transformation, taking advantage of the *Agrobacterium*s T-DNA sequence that allows natural insertion of genetic material into plant cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Other methods include biolistics, where particles of gold or tungsten are coated with DNA and then shot into young plant cells, and electroporation, which involves using an electric shock to make the cell membrane permeable to plasmid DNA.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] As only a single cell is transformed with genetic material, the organism must be regenerated from that single cell.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In plants, this is accomplished through the use of tissue culture.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In animals, it is necessary to ensure that the inserted DNA is present in the embryonic stem cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Bacteria consist of a single cell and reproduce clonally, so regeneration is not necessary.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Selectable markers are used to easily differentiate transformed from untransformed cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These markers are usually present in the transgenic organism, although a number of strategies have been developed that can remove the selectable marker from the mature transgenic plant.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Further testing using PCR, Southern hybridization, and DNA sequencing is conducted to confirm that an organism contains the new gene.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These tests can also confirm the chromosomal location and copy number of the inserted gene.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The presence of the gene does not guarantee it will be expressed at appropriate levels in the target tissue so methods that look for and measure the gene products (RNA and protein) are also used.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These include northern hybridisation, quantitative RT-PCR, Western blot, immunofluorescence, ELISA, and phenotypic analysis.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The new genetic material can be inserted randomly within the host genome or targeted to a specific location.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The technique of gene targeting uses homologous recombination to make desired changes to a specific endogenous gene.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This tends to occur at a relatively low frequency in plants and animals and generally requires the use of selectable markers.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The frequency of gene targeting can be greatly enhanced through genome editing.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genome editing utilizes artificially engineered nucleases that create specific double-stranded breaks at desired locations in the genome, and use the cell's endogenous mechanisms to repair the induced break by the natural processes of homologous recombination and nonhomologous end-joining.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] There are four families of engineered nucleases: meganucleases, zinc finger nucleases, transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs), and the Cas9-guideRNA system (adapted from CRISPR).
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] TALEN and CRISPR are the two most commonly used, and each has its own advantages.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] TALENs have greater target specificity, while CRISPR is easier to design and more efficient.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In addition to enhancing gene targeting, engineered nucleases can be used to introduce mutations at endogenous genes that generate a gene knockout.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has applications in medicine, research, industry, and agriculture, and can be used on a wide range of plants, animals, and microorganisms.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Bacteria, the first organisms to be genetically modified, can have plasmid DNA inserted containing new genes that code for medicines or enzymes that process food and other substrates.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Plants have been modified for insect protection, herbicide resistance, virus resistance, enhanced nutrition, tolerance to environmental pressures, and the production of edible vaccines.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Most commercialised GMOs are insect-resistant or herbicide-tolerant crop plants.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetically modified animals have been used for research, model animals, and the production of agricultural or pharmaceutical products.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The genetically modified animals include animals with genes knocked out, increased susceptibility to disease, hormones for extra growth, and the ability to express proteins in their milk.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has many applications to medicine that include the manufacturing of drugs, the creation of model animals that mimic human conditions, and gene therapy.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] One of the earliest uses of genetic engineering was to mass-produce human insulin in bacteria.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This application has now been applied to human growth hormones, follicle-stimulating hormones (for treating infertility), human albumin, monoclonal antibodies, antihemophilic factors, vaccines, and many other drugs.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Mouse hybridomas, cells fused together to create monoclonal antibodies, have been adapted through genetic engineering to create human monoclonal antibodies.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetically engineered viruses are being developed that can still confer immunity, but lack the infectious sequences.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is also used to create animal models of human diseases.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetically modified mice are the most common genetically engineered animal model.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] They have been used to study and model cancer (the oncomouse), obesity, heart disease, diabetes, arthritis, substance abuse, anxiety, aging, and Parkinson's disease.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Potential cures can be tested against these mouse models.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Gene therapy is the genetic engineering of humans, generally by replacing defective genes with effective ones.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Clinical research using somatic gene therapy has been conducted with several diseases, including X-linked SCID, chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), and Parkinson's disease.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2012, Alipogene tiparvovec became the first gene therapy treatment to be approved for clinical use.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2015, a virus was used to insert a healthy gene into the skin cells of a boy suffering from a rare skin disease, epidermolysis bullosa, in order to grow, and then graft healthy skin onto 80 percent of the boy's body, which was affected by the illness.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Germline gene therapy would result in any change being inheritable, which has raised concerns within the scientific community.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2015, CRISPR was used to edit the DNA of non-viable human embryos, leading scientists of major world academies to call for a moratorium on inheritable human genome edits.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] There are also concerns that the technology could be used not just for treatment, but for enhancement, modification, or alteration of a human beings' appearance, adaptability, intelligence, character, or behavior.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The distinction between cure and enhancement can also be difficult to establish.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In November 2018, He Jiankui announced that he had edited the genomes of two human embryos, to attempt to disable the *CCR5* gene, which codes for a receptor that HIV uses to enter cells.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The work was widely condemned as unethical, dangerous, and premature.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Currently, germline modification is banned in 40 countries.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Scientists who perform this type of research will often let embryos grow for a few days without allowing them to develop into a baby.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Researchers are altering the genome of pigs to induce the growth of human organs, with the aim of increasing the success of pig-to-human organ transplantation.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Scientists are creating "gene drives", changing the genomes of mosquitoes to make them immune to malaria, and then looking to spread the genetically altered mosquitoes throughout the mosquito population in the hopes of eliminating the disease.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is an important tool for natural scientists, with the creation of transgenic organisms one of the most important tools for the analysis of gene function.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genes and other genetic information from a wide range of organisms can be inserted into bacteria for storage and modification, creating genetically modified bacteria in the process .
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Bacteria are cheap, easy to grow, clonal, multiply quickly, relatively easy to transform, and can be stored at -80 °C almost indefinitely.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Once a gene is isolated, it can be stored inside the bacteria, providing an unlimited supply for research.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Organisms are genetically engineered to discover the functions of certain genes.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This could be the effect on the phenotype of the organism, where the gene is expressed or what other genes it interacts with.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These experiments generally involve loss of function, gain of function, tracking, and expression.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Organisms can have their cells transformed with a gene coding for a useful protein, such as an enzyme, so that they will overexpress the desired protein.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Mass quantities of the protein can then be manufactured by growing the transformed organism in bioreactor equipment using industrial fermentation, and then purifying the protein.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Some genes do not work well in bacteria, so yeast, insect cells or mammalian cells can also be used.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These techniques are used to produce medicines such as insulin, human growth hormone, and vaccines, supplements such as tryptophan, aid in the production of food (chymosin in cheese making) and fuels.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Other applications with genetically engineered bacteria could involve making them perform tasks outside their natural cycle, such as making biofuels, cleaning up oil spills, carbon and other toxic waste and detecting arsenic in drinking water.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Certain genetically modified microbes can also be used in biomining and bioremediation, due to their ability to extract heavy metals from their environment and incorporate them into compounds that are more easily recoverable.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In materials science, a genetically modified virus has been used in a research laboratory as a scaffold for assembling a more environmentally friendly lithium-ion battery.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Bacteria have also been engineered to function as sensors by expressing a fluorescent protein under certain environmental conditions.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] One of the best-known and controversial applications of genetic engineering is the creation and use of genetically modified crops or genetically modified livestock to produce genetically modified food.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Crops have been developed to increase production, increase tolerance to abiotic stresses, alter the composition of the food, or to produce novel products.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The first crops to be released commercially on a large scale provided protection from insect pests or tolerance to herbicides.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Fungal and virus resistant crops have also been developed or are in development.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] This makes the insect and weed management of crops easier and can indirectly increase crop yield.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] GM crops that directly improve yield by accelerating growth or making the plant more hardy (by improving salt, cold or drought tolerance) are also under development.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In 2016 Salmon have been genetically modified with growth hormones to reach normal adult size much faster.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] GMOs have been developed that modify the quality of produce by increasing the nutritional value or providing more industrially useful qualities or quantities.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The Amflora potato produces a more industrially useful blend of starches.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Soybeans and canola have been genetically modified to produce more healthy oils.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The first commercialised GM food was a tomato that had delayed ripening, increasing its shelf life.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Plants and animals have been engineered to produce materials they do not normally make.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Pharming uses crops and animals as bioreactors to produce vaccines, drug intermediates, or the drugs themselves; the useful product is purified from the harvest and then used in the standard pharmaceutical production process.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Cows and goats have been engineered to express drugs and other proteins in their milk, and in 2009 the FDA approved a drug produced in goat milk.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has potential applications in conservation and natural area management.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Gene transfer through viral vectors has been proposed as a means of controlling invasive species as well as vaccinating threatened fauna from disease.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Transgenic trees have been suggested as a way to confer resistance to pathogens in wild populations.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] With the increasing risks of maladaptation in organisms as a result of climate change and other perturbations, facilitated adaptation through gene tweaking could be one solution to reducing extinction risks.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Applications of genetic engineering in conservation are thus far mostly theoretical and have yet to be put into practice.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is also being used to create microbial art.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Some bacteria have been genetically engineered to create black and white photographs.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Novelty items such as lavender-colored carnations, blue roses, and glowing fish, have also been produced through genetic engineering.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The regulation of genetic engineering concerns the approaches taken by governments to assess and manage the risks associated with the development and release of GMOs.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The development of a regulatory framework began in 1975, at Asilomar, California.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The Asilomar meeting recommended a set of voluntary guidelines regarding the use of recombinant technology.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] As the technology improved the US established a committee at the Office of Science and Technology, which assigned regulatory approval of GM food to the USDA, FDA and EPA.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety, an international treaty that governs the transfer, handling, and use of GMOs, was adopted on 29 January 2000.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] One hundred and fifty-seven countries are members of the Protocol, and many use it as a reference point for their own regulations.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The legal and regulatory status of GM foods varies by country, with some nations banning or restricting them, and others permitting them with widely differing degrees of regulation.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Some countries allow the import of GM food with authorisation, but either do not allow its cultivation (Russia, Norway, Israel) or have provisions for cultivation even though no GM products are yet produced (Japan, South Korea).
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Most countries that do not allow GMO cultivation do permit research.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Some of the most marked differences occur between the US and Europe.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The US policy focuses on the product (not the process), only looks at verifiable scientific risks and uses the concept of substantial equivalence.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The European Union by contrast has possibly the most stringent GMO regulations in the world.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] All GMOs, along with irradiated food, are considered "new food" and subject to extensive, case-by-case, science-based food evaluation by the European Food Safety Authority.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The criteria for authorisation fall in four broad categories: "safety", "freedom of choice", "labelling", and "traceability".
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The level of regulation in other countries that cultivate GMOs lie in between Europe and the United States.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] One of the key issues concerning regulators is whether GM products should be labeled.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The European Commission says that mandatory labeling and traceability are needed to allow for informed choice, avoid potential false advertising and facilitate the withdrawal of products if adverse effects on health or the environment are discovered.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] The American Medical Association and the American Association for the Advancement of Science say that absent scientific evidence of harm even voluntary labeling is misleading and will falsely alarm consumers.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Labeling of GMO products in the marketplace is required in 64 countries.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Labeling can be mandatory up to a threshold GM content level (which varies between countries) or voluntary.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In Canada and the US labeling of GM food is voluntary, while in Europe all food (including processed food) or feed which contains greater than 0.9% of approved GMOs must be labelled.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Critics have objected to the use of genetic engineering on several grounds, including ethical, ecological and economic concerns.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Many of these concerns involve GM crops and whether food produced from them is safe and what impact growing them will have on the environment.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] These controversies have led to litigation, international trade disputes, and protests, and to restrictive regulation of commercial products in some countries.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Accusations that scientists are "playing God" and other religious issues have been ascribed to the technology from the beginning.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Other ethical issues raised include the patenting of life, the use of intellectual property rights, the level of labeling on products, control of the food supply and the objectivity of the regulatory process.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Although doubts have been raised, economically most studies have found growing GM crops to be beneficial to farmers.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Gene flow between GM crops and compatible plants, along with increased use of selective herbicides, can increase the risk of "superweeds" developing.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Other environmental concerns involve potential impacts on non-target organisms, including soil microbes, and an increase in secondary and resistant insect pests.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Many of the environmental impacts regarding GM crops may take many years to be understood and are also evident in conventional agriculture practices.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] With the commercialisation of genetically modified fish there are concerns over what the environmental consequences will be if they escape.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] There are three main concerns over the safety of genetically modified food: whether they may provoke an allergic reaction; whether the genes could transfer from the food into human cells; and whether the genes not approved for human consumption could outcross to other crops.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] There is a scientific consensus that currently available food derived from GM crops poses no greater risk to human health than conventional food, but that each GM food needs to be tested on a case-by-case basis before introduction.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Nonetheless, members of the public are less likely than scientists to perceive GM foods as safe.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering features in many science fiction stories.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Frank Herbert's novel *The White Plague* describes the deliberate use of genetic engineering to create a pathogen which specifically kills women.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Another of Herbert's creations, the *Dune* series of novels, uses genetic engineering to create the powerful Tleilaxu.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Few films have informed audiences about genetic engineering, with the exception of the 1978 *The Boys from Brazil* and the 1993 *Jurassic Park*, both of which make use of a lesson, a demonstration, and a clip of scientific film.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering methods are weakly represented in film; Michael Clark, writing for the Wellcome Trust, calls the portrayal of genetic engineering and biotechnology "seriously distorted" in films such as *The 6th Day*.
[src:alan-mchughen/genetic-engineering] In Clark's view, the biotechnology is typically "given fantastic but visually arresting forms" while the science is either relegated to the background or fictionalised to suit a young audience.
